
Urban drainage systems play a vital role in maintaining the stability and hygiene of modern cities; however, they are frequently affected by blockages, overflow conditions, and the accumulation of hazardous gases, which can lead to severe urban flooding and pose life-threatening risks to sanitation workers. Traditional drainage monitoring methods largely depend on manual inspection, which is inefficient, time-consuming, and exposes workers to dangerous environments without prior safety assessment. To address these challenges, this work proposes an integrated IoT-based Smart Drain Monitoring and Manhole Worker Safety System that combines real-time environmental sensing with intelligent decision-making and worker health monitoring to enhance both infrastructure management and occupational safety.

The proposed system utilizes a network of sensors, including ultrasonic sensors for continuous water level measurement, flow sensors for analyzing sewage movement, and gas sensors for detecting toxic gases such as carbon monoxide and hydrogen sulphide that are commonly present in drainage environments. These sensors are interfaced with an ESP32 microcontroller, which performs real-time data acquisition and processing. A key contribution of this system is the implementation of a multi-parameter decision-making approach, where blockage conditions are identified by correlating abnormal water level rise with reduced or stagnant flow, thereby significantly reducing false alarms caused by environmental variations such as rainfall.

In addition to monitoring drainage conditions, the system incorporates a wearable safety band designed for sanitation workers, equipped with sensors to monitor body temperature, detect motion or inactivity, and provide a manual panic alert mechanism. This enables continuous supervision of the worker’s physical condition during operations inside manholes. The system further enhances safety through an intelligent entry permission mechanism that evaluates environmental parameters such as gas concentration and water level before allowing workers to enter, effectively preventing exposure to hazardous conditions.

Furthermore, the system integrates priority-based alert classification, real-time status visualization, and rain-aware filtering logic to ensure accurate and context-aware operation under varying environmental conditions. All collected data is transmitted wirelessly to a centralized monitoring platform, allowing municipal authorities to receive real-time alerts, assess drainage conditions, assign maintenance tasks efficiently, and initiate emergency responses when required. Overall, the proposed solution offers a low-cost, scalable, and practical approach for smart city applications, significantly improving drainage system reliability, reducing the risks associated with manual inspection, and enhancing worker safety through proactive monitoring and intelligent automation.
